1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:25,532
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassa

2
00:00:25,512 --> 00:00:30,161
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,308 --> 00:00:44,112
So this weekend we're just looking at this process of taking refuge, refuge in the precepts.

4
00:00:46,167 --> 00:00:59,954
And for fear of repeating myself tomorrow, I thought I'd just hang around the question of, you know, what is the spiritual search?

5
00:01:01,078 --> 00:01:03,042
What's the quality of faith?

6
00:01:03,643 --> 00:01:05,427
What role does doubt play in it?

7
00:01:05,546 --> 00:01:06,588
That sort of area.

8
00:01:11,361 --> 00:01:18,875
There must have been some point in human history where this sort of self-awareness arose.

9
00:01:24,204 --> 00:01:32,239
And with it there must have somehow dawned the question of, you know, like, who am I?

10
00:01:32,876 --> 00:02:01,382
what am I doing here there must have been at some point who knows when where there were these fundamental questions must have slowly arisen and you know these three questions like who am I and how do I relate and what do I do

11
00:02:03,656 --> 00:02:08,462
And these congealed over time into what are discernible three paths.

12
00:02:09,925 --> 00:02:13,269
Hinduism, I think, has very clearly delineated.

13
00:02:13,329 --> 00:02:17,913
But of course it's there in all the spiritual traditions.

14
00:02:17,933 --> 00:02:23,480
And in the Buddha, in the Buddhism, it's enshrined in the Eightfold Path.

15
00:02:23,501 --> 00:02:28,247
So right understanding is trying to answer the question, well, who am I?

16
00:02:30,116 --> 00:02:30,978
Or why am I?

17
00:02:33,241 --> 00:02:39,087
And the right attitude is, now that I'm here, how do I relate?

18
00:02:39,407 --> 00:02:43,592
What is my relationship to other people, to the universe?

19
00:02:44,354 --> 00:02:45,194
How should I relate?

20
00:02:46,295 --> 00:02:48,298
And then that moves into action.

21
00:02:48,639 --> 00:02:53,104
So now that I've understood why I'm here and how I should relate, what do I do?

22
00:02:53,606 --> 00:02:57,252
And that's the path of karma, so path of gnosis or understanding.

23
00:02:58,334 --> 00:03:01,058
The path of love, that's what relate.

24
00:03:01,498 --> 00:03:04,524
When you ask the question, how do I relate, you're really asking, what is love?

25
00:03:05,725 --> 00:03:07,989
And then finally, what do I do?

26
00:03:13,437 --> 00:03:21,370
And according to the Buddha, these sorts of questions arise out of suffering.

27
00:03:22,260 --> 00:03:25,686
So this word dukkha, it has various meanings.

28
00:03:25,825 --> 00:03:47,879
So it's not just the awful physical suffering that we can go through or mental distress, but it's at that deeper sort of spiritual level, a sort of sense of alienation, sort of an existential, a feeling of meaninglessness.

29
00:03:50,020 --> 00:04:16,821
meaninglessness and that can come across hard to people and it ends up as being a sort of can be a real deep depressive sort of state of living without any meaning especially in our society which at least on the surface is just driven by a hunt for the next exciting thing to do

30
00:04:18,050 --> 00:04:20,072
What's the next film?

31
00:04:21,495 --> 00:04:22,555
What's the next kick?

32
00:04:22,596 --> 00:04:23,677
What's the next buzz?

33
00:04:23,798 --> 00:04:29,086
It's like we're constantly searching for something to distract the mind.

34
00:04:31,649 --> 00:04:43,745
And you're constantly fed the understanding that pleasure and the pleasures of relationship are equated to happiness.

35
00:04:43,946 --> 00:04:46,470
Like this car will definitely make you happy.

36
00:04:47,783 --> 00:04:48,103
you know.

37
00:04:53,391 --> 00:05:03,305
And we know just because of the nature of things, because of the nature of the transience, the ephemeral nature of things, the fact that things arise and pass away, change.

38
00:05:04,786 --> 00:05:05,728
But that can't be so.

39
00:05:06,168 --> 00:05:07,850
But that, it's not as though

40
00:05:08,235 --> 00:05:10,137
And we grasp that.

41
00:05:10,459 --> 00:05:12,942
There's still within us this search for happiness.

42
00:05:12,982 --> 00:05:22,673
Now, none of us here may be drug addicts or completely lost in that commercialism, in that consumerism.

43
00:05:22,892 --> 00:05:23,454
We might not.

44
00:05:23,533 --> 00:05:24,175
We might know that.

45
00:05:24,214 --> 00:05:27,579
But even so, we still do it.

46
00:05:27,819 --> 00:05:31,262
We still seek happiness in a cup of tea, Costa coffee.

47
00:05:32,625 --> 00:05:32,725
Yeah.

48
00:05:33,785 --> 00:05:37,250
It's like you're always looking for a place where you can find relief.

49
00:05:37,851 --> 00:05:39,274
You know, it's like, and that's your refuge.

50
00:05:39,855 --> 00:05:48,651
Every time you do that, what you're saying is that Costa Coffee is my refuge.

51
00:05:48,670 --> 00:05:50,814
You go in there and choose a cake, you see.

52
00:05:50,834 --> 00:05:54,882
So next time you do that and you know you're going in there really just to escape boredom or

53
00:05:55,637 --> 00:05:56,098
or whatever.

54
00:05:56,559 --> 00:06:01,043
It's hard to really rationalize or to give some real purpose to coffee.

55
00:06:01,944 --> 00:06:11,036
But having done so, one can sit there and gaze at it and say, I am taking refuge in coffee.

56
00:06:13,317 --> 00:06:15,279
And let that sort of sink in a while.

57
00:06:15,319 --> 00:06:16,942
You shouldn't stop drinking the coffee.

58
00:06:17,262 --> 00:06:20,305
It's just acknowledging that.

59
00:06:20,565 --> 00:06:24,531
It's not going to really give what the heart really seeks.

60
00:06:28,577 --> 00:06:31,884
And if you were to ask, well, what does the heart want?

61
00:06:32,184 --> 00:06:33,266
What does the heart want?

62
00:06:33,666 --> 00:06:36,711
Now, mind the head, understanding, why is this, why is that?

63
00:06:37,372 --> 00:06:39,016
Where does the heart want to be?

64
00:06:40,377 --> 00:06:41,740
If you ask yourself that question.

65
00:06:45,668 --> 00:06:50,956
Now, even the heart can be confused, can be doubting as to where it wants to be.

66
00:06:51,718 --> 00:06:54,062
So, as I say, a lot of people would

67
00:06:55,257 --> 00:07:02,065
would want to place their heart in a relationship, trusting a relationship, trying to find the right person.

68
00:07:02,105 --> 00:07:06,692
That's going to be the wherewithal of our lives.

69
00:07:12,298 --> 00:07:14,240
Taking refuge in somebody else, you see.

70
00:07:15,702 --> 00:07:18,125
But that's unreliable, isn't it?

71
00:07:20,317 --> 00:07:49,598
people who were deeply in love end up stabbing each other when people take the vow to to marry to take care of and all the lovely things that they say till death do us part sort of an idealism isn't it it's like

72
00:07:50,978 --> 00:07:54,605
And there's a presumption in that ceremony that it is actually going to happen.

73
00:07:56,689 --> 00:07:59,555
And a few years down the line it sort of corrupts.

74
00:07:59,574 --> 00:08:03,062
Even if it doesn't corrupt and people fall apart and go separate ways.

75
00:08:05,045 --> 00:08:11,197
There's that confusion often between what love is and what the emotion that we call love is.

76
00:08:12,663 --> 00:08:19,629
And I remember going, I remember doing a little ceremony for people who were getting married.

77
00:08:20,711 --> 00:08:26,216
And it was combined with a sort of New Age-y ceremony.

78
00:08:27,619 --> 00:08:28,240
It was very lovely.

79
00:08:29,281 --> 00:08:30,701
And they asked me to say something.

80
00:08:31,322 --> 00:08:39,851
And when I pointed out that love, real love, had nothing to do with emotions, like there was a

81
00:08:40,422 --> 00:09:10,327
a sort of stunned silence in the room like that you know like what is it then if it's not and what we discover of course is that love is an attitude it's a disposition it's a way of relating whether you like somebody or not I mean that's the one of the good things about the spiritual life that when we're practicing together we're all helping each other it's irrelevant whether we like each other or not

82
00:09:12,147 --> 00:09:18,335
And often the person whom you don't like, the person who's sort of disturbing you, is your teacher.

83
00:09:18,816 --> 00:09:23,380
They're telling you where your buttons are.

84
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:33,955
I once, a long time ago, did a retreat and there was this, you know, in the Eastern tradition all the men sit together and the women sit over there.

85
00:09:34,596 --> 00:09:35,657
And there was this man and he was

86
00:09:37,256 --> 00:09:39,298
for six days, sniffing.

87
00:09:40,179 --> 00:09:45,044
Have you ever sat next to somebody sniffing all the time?

88
00:09:45,065 --> 00:09:51,991
Now, I wouldn't want to shock you with what I was going to do with that man's nose.

89
00:09:52,011 --> 00:10:03,784
And the teacher at the time, it was Ajahn Sumedho actually, some of you will know him, took a break on Thursday, and he thought he was getting too tight or something.

90
00:10:04,044 --> 00:10:07,028
And I happened to mention this to another man,

91
00:10:07,429 --> 00:10:10,293
and asked him if this nose was also upsetting him.

92
00:10:11,535 --> 00:10:14,921
And to my amazement, he hadn't even heard it.

93
00:10:14,941 --> 00:10:15,600
He hadn't even heard it.

94
00:10:16,903 --> 00:10:17,804
I said, oh, fine.

95
00:10:18,445 --> 00:10:23,351
And at the end of the retreat, because we had another day to go, he came to me and he says, I did hear it.

96
00:10:23,371 --> 00:10:24,714
He said, oh, yesterday.

97
00:10:25,855 --> 00:10:29,059
Is that what happened with unwholesome speech?

98
00:10:30,722 --> 00:10:31,583
Maybe I shouldn't have said it.

99
00:10:31,604 --> 00:10:31,964
I don't know.

100
00:10:31,984 --> 00:10:34,248
But he was obviously more annoyed with me than the man's nose.

101
00:10:35,129 --> 00:10:37,351
He hadn't heard it.

102
00:10:40,504 --> 00:10:46,153
So, asking ourselves the question, you know, where does the heart want to be?

103
00:10:46,173 --> 00:10:51,099
It wants to be content, doesn't it?

104
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:56,086
Isn't that the sort of deepest place you want to be?

105
00:10:56,225 --> 00:10:57,168
To be content.

106
00:10:58,028 --> 00:10:59,910
And what does that mean, to be content?

107
00:11:01,173 --> 00:11:09,364
To accept the way things are, no matter what they are, whether they're pleasant or unpleasant, a sort of acceptance.

108
00:11:11,317 --> 00:11:16,807
But not with resignation, resignation suggesting some sort of despair, I can't do anything about it.

109
00:11:18,249 --> 00:11:22,836
But more that sort of openness, this is the way it is.

110
00:11:25,782 --> 00:11:37,139
And then in seeing the situation clearly, as clearly as we can, always, because we're in a process of time, you know, time moves, possibilities arise, you know.

111
00:11:43,177 --> 00:11:53,701
So searching that contentment and then, as it were, I mean, what I'm suggesting is that that's what we're deeply searching for.

112
00:11:54,201 --> 00:11:57,328
So it might start off with just wanting to put an end to suffering.

113
00:11:57,950 --> 00:11:59,273
You know, it might be phrased that way.

114
00:11:59,373 --> 00:12:00,816
It's definitely how the Buddha started.

115
00:12:02,686 --> 00:12:11,620
He set out quite clearly, and then he says it himself, quite clearly because he was in a state of confusion, a state of suffering.

116
00:12:12,022 --> 00:12:14,105
So he goes off searching for the end of suffering.

117
00:12:19,453 --> 00:12:20,154
And...

118
00:12:21,653 --> 00:12:33,424
As we go searching, as we go into various different types of teachings, somehow we have to make a connection with that teaching, if it's going to work for us.

119
00:12:34,265 --> 00:12:35,748
And that's really what we mean by faith.

120
00:12:38,410 --> 00:12:42,554
And a lot of people go through the process of listening.

121
00:12:42,934 --> 00:12:45,477
They listen to the teaching or read about it.

122
00:12:47,080 --> 00:12:50,243
And this brings up a certain confidence, because that's what faith is.

123
00:12:52,214 --> 00:12:55,038
a certain confidence in what they're hearing.

124
00:12:56,961 --> 00:12:57,761
So it's not a belief.

125
00:12:59,164 --> 00:13:13,746
If what we mean by belief is a sort of a total acceptance of a statement, that would be an error in terms of the Buddha, because what belief does is it stops you investigating, it stops you taking the process any further.

126
00:13:14,227 --> 00:13:17,352
You take refuge in a mental state of belief.

127
00:13:17,812 --> 00:13:19,655
I believe so, I'm all right, I'll be saved.

128
00:13:21,289 --> 00:13:25,475
That's also a false refuge.

129
00:13:25,495 --> 00:13:26,275
It might make you high.

130
00:13:27,898 --> 00:13:28,759
Like, I'm free now.

131
00:13:29,240 --> 00:13:30,120
I believe, you know.

132
00:13:31,042 --> 00:13:31,802
I believe in God.

133
00:13:31,842 --> 00:13:32,683
I believe in the Buddha.

134
00:13:34,346 --> 00:13:35,607
Now I can go and have my Costa coffee.

135
00:13:37,791 --> 00:13:40,274
It all takes away a whole area of problems.

136
00:13:40,394 --> 00:13:40,754
I believe.

137
00:13:41,394 --> 00:13:42,155
That's it.

138
00:13:42,756 --> 00:13:43,317
I don't worry about it.

139
00:13:44,719 --> 00:13:46,260
But that stops the investigation.

140
00:13:46,301 --> 00:13:48,663
That stops the process of

141
00:13:50,450 --> 00:13:53,114
trying to find out whether it's true for me personally.

142
00:13:53,715 --> 00:14:07,277
Now, what we discover, of course, is that the next step, having heard something, we then begin to think about it ourselves, so that this knowledge that we've picked up becomes our own particular way of thinking.

143
00:14:08,198 --> 00:14:10,702
We've thought it through ourselves, to some extent.

144
00:14:12,302 --> 00:14:18,214
But then we get this practice, we get this direct experience of the path, this direct.

145
00:14:19,134 --> 00:14:34,142
And of course, it's in the practice that we're not only, shall we say, stabilizing that faith through the practice because it actually works, but the very practice is itself the process of liberation.

146
00:14:38,256 --> 00:14:46,051
Now that faith is an ability to be open, to be willing to have a go, to keep going.

147
00:14:46,451 --> 00:14:49,457
All of you must have that or you simply wouldn't be here.

148
00:14:49,938 --> 00:14:51,782
So it's there within you, you see.

149
00:14:53,905 --> 00:14:57,091
There are people who don't need to go through that.

150
00:14:58,438 --> 00:15:06,221
Sometimes on seeing a person, like they just feel it's their path, it's their way.

151
00:15:07,224 --> 00:15:08,668
In my own case, both happened.

152
00:15:09,129 --> 00:15:13,782
I entered into the Buddhist path in that sort of gingerly way.

153
00:15:13,761 --> 00:15:18,347
of investigating this, investigating that, you know, having a go.

154
00:15:18,368 --> 00:15:23,354
I mean, I didn't, there wasn't the choice when I started in the 70s, middle 70s.

155
00:15:26,177 --> 00:15:37,812
But I remember at one point, when I was with a teacher, there was a very direct, clear connection that this was my teacher.

156
00:15:39,562 --> 00:15:41,865
and I went to Burma to be with him.

157
00:15:41,966 --> 00:15:46,131
I didn't stay that long, but it was very clear.

158
00:15:46,591 --> 00:15:48,495
I never had that with anybody else.

159
00:15:48,514 --> 00:15:58,346
I've had lots of teachers, I've had lots of people I've been with, but I just knew that this person was going to get me through, was going to really make it for me.

160
00:16:00,629 --> 00:16:04,895
So that leap of faith which sometimes happens in the heart is also

161
00:16:05,533 --> 00:16:08,096
you know, a proper act of faith.

162
00:16:09,698 --> 00:16:26,017
And in a sense it's much more strong than a faith which arises through thought, because it's coming from that deeper level within us, that sort of deep connection.

163
00:16:26,297 --> 00:16:30,461
There's that case of Anathapindika in the scriptures, who's a merchant,

164
00:16:30,981 --> 00:16:36,567
It was the time when merchants were really becoming a very rich caste or class.

165
00:16:37,087 --> 00:16:38,990
The castes weren't so rigid in those days.

166
00:16:40,150 --> 00:16:49,179
And I think it was his brother-in-law or his brother had met the Buddha and had actually set up a little monastery for him.

167
00:16:50,081 --> 00:16:57,748
And while he was visiting an Atapindika, he mentioned about the Buddha and it would seem that just the word, the Buddha,

168
00:16:57,863 --> 00:17:02,047
seemed to have awoken in him this enormous connection already.

169
00:17:03,249 --> 00:17:18,845
And he went on to become a great supporter, bought him land for a monastery and stuff like that, and was forever supporting the Buddha.

170
00:17:19,125 --> 00:17:25,271
But that was just sort of an immediate connection, even by a word, sort of something in the air, you might say.

171
00:17:28,171 --> 00:17:32,196
I've known people to do that from pictures, you know, of Indian gurus.

172
00:17:32,217 --> 00:17:34,980
Just seeing a picture, they've sort of made that connection.

173
00:17:38,144 --> 00:17:39,006
Nobody's done it with me.

174
00:17:42,851 --> 00:17:44,634
Hang on, I've got to get older.

175
00:17:47,678 --> 00:17:55,067
So it's that sort of, there are these two ways in which one can make that sort of faith.

176
00:17:55,087 --> 00:17:56,128
It's a confidence, isn't it?

177
00:17:56,450 --> 00:17:56,710
Now,

178
00:17:56,892 --> 00:17:58,153
You can't move without that.

179
00:17:59,836 --> 00:18:03,963
You can't commit yourself without confidence.

180
00:18:03,983 --> 00:18:06,027
And that's not just the spiritual part, it's anything.

181
00:18:06,407 --> 00:18:11,797
Whether it's a job, sometimes you wonder whether you can do it, whether you should be doing it.

182
00:18:12,597 --> 00:18:15,281
And if there isn't that confidence, you can't take the job.

183
00:18:16,364 --> 00:18:19,067
Or you do it feeling really fearful about it.

184
00:18:20,631 --> 00:18:23,675
Same with a relationship, whether you want to start a relationship with somebody.

185
00:18:24,532 --> 00:18:29,019
or cement a relationship, either a partnership or a marriage.

186
00:18:29,719 --> 00:18:37,409
If you're in a state of doubt, well, I might be, I don't know whether I should, maybe I can't, and all this sort of stuff, you can't commit yourself.

187
00:18:37,429 --> 00:18:43,457
So that sense of confidence, trusting, to trust, has to be there.

188
00:18:44,157 --> 00:18:48,583
And in the actual spiritual path, the trust is

189
00:18:49,811 --> 00:19:18,721
likely to do with ourselves I think I mean you can trust the teacher you can trust the teaching but eventually you've got to have a trust in yourself you see and some people have a lot of problems with that have a lot of problems with doubt one way or the other I shall leave exactly what it is we're putting our trust in like the Buddha Dhamma Sangha till tomorrow you'll all fall asleep tomorrow

190
00:19:21,924 --> 00:19:32,904
But here's a case where, and this gives you an idea of how quickly one can sort of take refuge in the Buddha.

191
00:19:33,567 --> 00:19:36,432
There's a Brahmin Janusoni and he comes to see the Buddha.

192
00:19:36,952 --> 00:19:38,957
And it's basically a question about practice.

193
00:19:38,977 --> 00:19:41,121
So this Brahmin is obviously a practitioner.

194
00:19:42,282 --> 00:19:43,545
And he says to the Buddha,

195
00:19:44,470 --> 00:19:51,577
You know, people who go into the jungle, into the forests, and live on their own, they go mad.

196
00:19:52,057 --> 00:19:57,824
And is that not your experience, that people go mad when they go off by themselves?

197
00:19:58,505 --> 00:20:02,730
So there's obviously in those days, there were lots of these men, mainly.

198
00:20:02,769 --> 00:20:12,519
There were a few women, but it was difficult for a woman to do it because there wasn't the protection against men.

199
00:20:14,676 --> 00:20:17,961
So all these men were going off, doing a sort of hippie trip.

200
00:20:17,981 --> 00:20:20,265
That happened in the 60s and 70s.

201
00:20:21,266 --> 00:20:25,451
And searching for this enlightenment, this liberation.

202
00:20:26,614 --> 00:20:31,420
And obviously some of them were going bonkers out there.

203
00:20:32,121 --> 00:20:33,323
They were sort of losing it.

204
00:20:33,963 --> 00:20:40,794
And the Buddha then goes into quite a clear definition of what it is that stops you going mad.

205
00:20:40,834 --> 00:20:43,317
And the two main things are

206
00:20:43,786 --> 00:20:53,118
that your virtue is good, that you're not going into that sort of situation with huge guilts and problems and whatnot.

207
00:20:53,480 --> 00:20:55,001
That has to be cleared, as it were.

208
00:20:55,301 --> 00:21:04,895
And also, even if you have that sort of thing, you're very clear that from now on you are virtuous, and that gives you a sort of solid rock within yourself.

209
00:21:06,176 --> 00:21:07,719
And the other thing is a disciplined mind.

210
00:21:08,560 --> 00:21:12,425
Because as we know in our meditation, if the mind's not disciplined, it goes bonkers.

211
00:21:13,553 --> 00:21:23,247
So, having said all this, Genosoni is really taken by it.

212
00:21:23,647 --> 00:21:39,310
And he also answers another question which is of interest, which I've mentioned before this weekend, is that he says to Genosoni that he keeps going to the forest for his own quiet abiding and as a teaching for others, as a good example for others.

213
00:21:40,031 --> 00:21:40,152
Right?

214
00:21:41,346 --> 00:21:47,634
And this is the sort of classic response that you get throughout the scriptures to various persons.

215
00:21:48,474 --> 00:21:55,021
Excellent good Gautama, so they would call him by his family name, your surname basically.

216
00:21:55,823 --> 00:22:10,779
Excellent good Gautama, it is as if one might set upright what has been upset or might disclose what was covered or show the way to one who has gone astray or bring an oil lamp into the darkness so that those with vision might see material shapes.

217
00:22:11,147 --> 00:22:17,777
Even so, in many a figure has the Dhamma been made clear by the Venerable Gautama.

218
00:22:18,438 --> 00:22:22,683
Thus I am going to the Venerable Gautama for refuge, the Dhamma and the Sangha.

219
00:22:23,183 --> 00:22:30,775
May the Blessed Gautama accept me as a lay follower, going for refuge from today forth as long as life lasts.

220
00:22:31,214 --> 00:22:35,201
So he's really taken back as long as life lasts.

221
00:22:35,221 --> 00:22:36,041
He's really taken back.

222
00:22:37,404 --> 00:22:40,388
But this wasn't always the case.

223
00:22:42,010 --> 00:22:42,790
And there's a lovely one.

224
00:22:44,093 --> 00:22:45,894
Well, there are two occasions, actually.

225
00:22:45,914 --> 00:22:50,180
But this one is a man called, who's termed Dandapan, which means sticking hand.

226
00:22:51,741 --> 00:22:54,945
And he asks the Buddha in a rather provocative way.

227
00:22:55,046 --> 00:22:57,108
He said, what does this recluse assert?

228
00:22:57,368 --> 00:22:58,750
What do you proclaim?

229
00:22:59,490 --> 00:23:06,720
So he responds to this by saying, I assert and proclaim

230
00:23:06,885 --> 00:23:11,113
that I do not quarrel with anybody, that the world quarrels with me.

231
00:23:11,133 --> 00:23:15,439
And then he goes on to explain the teaching.

232
00:23:15,460 --> 00:23:32,926
But even so, Dandapani, who was a Sakyan, he belonged to the same tribe that the Buddha did, shook his head, wagged his tongue, raised his eyebrows until his forehead puckered in three lines and then departed leaning on his stick.

233
00:23:34,307 --> 00:23:40,095
So even though the Buddha must have given him a really good old talk, he still went away with great doubts.

234
00:23:41,636 --> 00:23:51,127
And there's also a lovely thing which in a sense also shows us that after the Buddha was enlightened, he wasn't a natural teacher.

235
00:23:51,808 --> 00:23:58,576
He had to learn how to teach, just as he had to learn the path to liberation.

236
00:23:59,047 --> 00:24:08,488
He meets one of these Ajivakas, these ascetics, just as he's on his way to teach the five old former companions.

237
00:24:08,509 --> 00:24:17,950
So he's just become liberated, he's thought it through, and he's decided that he is going to try and teach it, and he meets this ascetic on the way.

238
00:24:17,930 --> 00:24:23,695
And the ascetic says, you've got lovely bright features, you know, you look absolutely splendid, who's your teacher and all that.

239
00:24:23,776 --> 00:24:30,083
And the Buddha goes into this amazing statement about, I have no teacher, I am the fully enlightened one, I am the liberated, you see.

240
00:24:30,624 --> 00:24:33,728
And the guy says, oh, that's very good, and walks off.

241
00:24:33,748 --> 00:24:37,531
As you would, if you think about it.

242
00:24:38,152 --> 00:24:42,798
If you stopped somebody in the street and said, well, you look, you know, you look a pretty spiritual advantage.

243
00:24:42,817 --> 00:24:46,121
And he says, well, I am the new cosmic Buddha, and I live in the north of London.

244
00:24:46,141 --> 00:24:47,682
We used to get letters like that.

245
00:24:47,663 --> 00:24:48,765
Yeah, the Vihara.

246
00:24:49,266 --> 00:24:50,548
I often wonder what happened to this guy.

247
00:24:51,689 --> 00:24:56,978
Every so often a letter would come to the Vihara saying that the next cosmic Buddha was living in Northern London.

248
00:24:59,080 --> 00:25:01,345
I never investigated it for fear he was.

249
00:25:01,986 --> 00:25:04,589
I mean, that's a changed me path.

250
00:25:06,472 --> 00:25:09,017
And of course that didn't work.

251
00:25:09,037 --> 00:25:13,704
I think he got the idea he had to be slightly more subtle.

252
00:25:19,269 --> 00:25:27,262
So once we've actually established this faith, once we've actually got this confidence, the question then is how do we make it grow?

253
00:25:27,303 --> 00:25:33,271
How do we take it to the point where it becomes not just a spiritual faculty but a spiritual strength?

254
00:25:34,273 --> 00:25:35,916
So it's one of the spiritual faculties.

255
00:25:36,698 --> 00:25:41,766
Faith, effort, awareness, concentration and wisdom.

256
00:25:42,006 --> 00:25:44,349
These are the five spiritual faculties as they're called.

257
00:25:45,645 --> 00:26:00,741
And it's only when we actually have a glimpse of nibbana, when we actually experience the ultimate point, even if it's only, as the Buddha said, like a flash of lightning, does that faith now become sort of rock solid, becomes a bala, becomes rock solid.

258
00:26:00,883 --> 00:26:02,564
You can't deny an experience.

259
00:26:03,806 --> 00:26:06,949
You can always, up until that point, say, well, maybe, maybe not, who knows.

260
00:26:08,310 --> 00:26:11,433
But once you've actually experienced it, then you can't deny it.

261
00:26:13,117 --> 00:26:16,883
And that's the conclusion, you might say, the fulfillment of faith.

262
00:26:22,151 --> 00:26:26,336
It's interesting in the Christian story, isn't it, where Peter denies Christ three times.

263
00:26:27,357 --> 00:26:31,242
Even though he knew in his heart, he knew that this was the great guru or whatever.

264
00:26:32,424 --> 00:26:36,190
And he denies him, of course, with tremendous remorse if you do that.

265
00:26:36,770 --> 00:26:41,116
You can't go against what you personally know, for fear in that case.

266
00:26:44,184 --> 00:26:49,292
And one of the things is good companionship.

267
00:26:49,313 --> 00:26:51,455
The Buddha is quite strong about that.

268
00:26:52,136 --> 00:27:06,078
Ananda, who was his companion for the last 20 years of his life, thought that, you know, Ananda used to make statements like, well, now I think I understand what you're on about.

269
00:27:06,098 --> 00:27:07,780
And the Buddha said, oh, no, no, Ananda, no.

270
00:27:07,882 --> 00:27:09,483
He said, no, you've got a long way to go yet.

271
00:27:10,527 --> 00:27:18,679
And on this occasion he said, I think that friendship, good friendship, good being with people is half the spiritual life.

272
00:27:18,699 --> 00:27:20,080
He says, oh no Ananda, no, no, no.

273
00:27:21,063 --> 00:27:22,124
He says the whole of it.

274
00:27:23,646 --> 00:27:28,934
This is the entire life, the livelihood, the entire way you're living Ananda.

275
00:27:28,974 --> 00:27:32,619
That is good friendship and companionship, good comradeship.

276
00:27:33,460 --> 00:27:41,174
When a meditator has a good friend, a good companion, a good comrade, it is expected that he would develop and cultivate the Noble Eightfold Path.

277
00:27:42,353 --> 00:27:51,383
And I think most of you who go to groups will know that to go to an evening group once a week or whatever is a real fillip.

278
00:27:51,763 --> 00:27:55,067
It sort of gives you that little bit of energy, that group energy.

279
00:27:56,308 --> 00:28:05,239
And coming here or going to a meditation center, it's not just the case of coming here to practice, but to actually be with people.

280
00:28:05,259 --> 00:28:10,605
And you go away imbued, as it were, with their confidence, with their energy.

281
00:28:16,188 --> 00:28:20,037
And then there are things which really support that commitment, that faith.

282
00:28:22,541 --> 00:28:23,565
It's a bit heavy, really.

283
00:28:23,585 --> 00:28:25,107
He says to be perfect in virtue.

284
00:28:25,147 --> 00:28:27,192
Well, that's a bit heavy.

285
00:28:27,815 --> 00:28:34,403
I think everybody here, but at least to move towards it, to move towards virtue.

286
00:28:34,984 --> 00:28:39,150
And we won't do that unless we make the connection between virtue and liberation.

287
00:28:40,412 --> 00:28:47,740
You can't be liberated, you can't be fully awakened without having been entirely purified.

288
00:28:47,821 --> 00:28:49,022
The one goes with the other.

289
00:28:49,503 --> 00:28:54,210
And the reason is simple, because all the...

290
00:28:54,190 --> 00:28:59,817
unwholesome, unskillful things that we do are the measure of our delusion.

291
00:29:00,642 --> 00:29:02,833
Once the delusion goes, then obviously...

292
00:29:03,573 --> 00:29:05,035
All that bad stuff goes too.

293
00:29:05,736 --> 00:29:06,696
But it works the other way.

294
00:29:06,757 --> 00:29:15,568
If you work against your bad stuff, the stuff that you see is unwholesome, then you must be growing in wisdom too.

295
00:29:16,430 --> 00:29:18,772
It sort of leans, the one moves towards the other.

296
00:29:19,394 --> 00:29:22,116
In the Eightfold Path, right understanding, right attitude.

297
00:29:22,357 --> 00:29:27,183
So we can start with right understanding, but you can also start with right attitude.

298
00:29:27,163 --> 00:29:35,201
So, for instance, you might start with saying to yourself to grow in compassion in some way.

299
00:29:35,280 --> 00:29:43,096
Whatever life presents itself to make that an opportunity for compassion through generosity, through helping, etc., etc.

300
00:29:43,853 --> 00:29:50,769
Now as you do that unwittingly, you're making that connection of interrelatedness between people.

301
00:29:51,991 --> 00:29:56,261
And that of course comes up as this business of being interdependent.

302
00:29:57,484 --> 00:30:02,757
So it doesn't matter which way you begin the process, the one will always affect the other.

303
00:30:05,571 --> 00:30:07,674
Training according to the rules of training.

304
00:30:07,734 --> 00:30:13,041
So here, although he's talking to monks, this is also to do with our precepts.

305
00:30:13,061 --> 00:30:16,046
The precepts that we take, the training rules.

306
00:30:16,066 --> 00:30:20,852
They're translated as precepts, but the actual word means training rule.

307
00:30:20,912 --> 00:30:22,474
It's an actual training.

308
00:30:24,096 --> 00:30:29,304
Engaging in talk concerning effacement.

309
00:30:29,324 --> 00:30:34,109
Not trying to put oneself first all the time or making big of oneself.

310
00:30:35,153 --> 00:30:36,797
Favouring the heart's release.

311
00:30:39,663 --> 00:30:47,220
And here we can say that that's to do with letting go of those attachments, letting go of those compulsive behaviours.

312
00:30:48,943 --> 00:30:51,529
And what the vipassana is doing is showing us how to do that.

313
00:30:51,951 --> 00:30:54,276
So we don't just do vipassana when we're sitting.

314
00:30:55,386 --> 00:31:05,083
Any time, you could be standing at the bus stop and you could feel this great desire to go into Costa Coffee, but you let it go.

315
00:31:05,103 --> 00:31:07,386
You just let it go, you let it go, you see.

316
00:31:08,709 --> 00:31:12,454
And you're observing the feeling, you're observing how strong it is.

317
00:31:15,901 --> 00:31:19,707
The energetic, be energetic in abandoning what is unprofitable.

318
00:31:20,057 --> 00:31:23,563
That's discerning what's unprofitable, but in abandoning it.

319
00:31:23,843 --> 00:31:26,165
You're making that determination, I'm not going to go down that path.

320
00:31:26,646 --> 00:31:27,807
I'm not going to do that again.

321
00:31:29,550 --> 00:31:39,523
And although that can feel painful and whatnot, remember that as soon as you stop doing something, you're withdrawing the energy from that conditioning.

322
00:31:39,544 --> 00:31:44,029
You're just withdrawing the energy from that conditioning.

323
00:31:44,049 --> 00:31:47,634
So if somebody has a habit, say, of smoking, the thing to do is to stop.

324
00:31:48,948 --> 00:31:51,171
And then, of course, you get the pain, you get the horror of it.

325
00:31:52,492 --> 00:31:53,453
But first of all, you have to stop.

326
00:31:53,654 --> 00:31:56,278
You have to say, no, I'm not doing it.

327
00:31:56,298 --> 00:32:03,669
So if you see anything that you're doing, anywhere where you feel a compulsive behavior, which is being imprisoned, isn't it?

328
00:32:03,729 --> 00:32:06,112
I mean, you become a prisoner of your desire.

329
00:32:06,492 --> 00:32:07,614
You know, it's sort of dragging you around.

330
00:32:07,673 --> 00:32:11,619
It's sort of hooked you by the nose and sort of, you know, come this way, come that way.

331
00:32:11,660 --> 00:32:14,584
I mean, it's dreadful.

332
00:32:16,453 --> 00:32:19,176
And developing, of course, what is profitable.

333
00:32:19,317 --> 00:32:21,259
So there's always the other side.

334
00:32:23,041 --> 00:32:27,166
When we start with the five precepts, that's things that we don't do.

335
00:32:27,788 --> 00:32:30,230
We try not to get involved in, even at a subtle level.

336
00:32:30,672 --> 00:32:31,972
But then there's always the opposite of that.

337
00:32:33,976 --> 00:32:42,385
And this is expressed in right attitude as moving from hatred to love, from cruelty to compassion, and from selfishness to generosity.

338
00:32:42,625 --> 00:32:45,549
So there's also the positive side of our actions.

339
00:32:47,690 --> 00:32:53,055
And interestingly enough, understanding impermanence.

340
00:32:53,075 --> 00:32:55,657
The Buddha seems to have centered on that one, the impermanence.

341
00:32:55,778 --> 00:32:57,019
And you might say, well, why is that?

342
00:32:57,759 --> 00:32:59,480
Why doesn't he center on suffering?

343
00:33:00,803 --> 00:33:08,190
You know, the psychological suffering, the process of desire, because it's there in the Four Noble Truths, the cause of suffering is desire.

344
00:33:08,210 --> 00:33:10,511
So why doesn't he plug that so much?

345
00:33:10,531 --> 00:33:13,815
I mean, he obviously plugs it, but it's this impermanence.

346
00:33:14,622 --> 00:33:17,184
And then there's the doctrine of anatam, not me, not mine.

347
00:33:17,925 --> 00:33:18,826
Why doesn't he go for that?

348
00:33:19,548 --> 00:33:24,193
And the reason is, it's because through impermanence that one can see the other two more clearly.

349
00:33:25,476 --> 00:33:31,183
So when you see that things are impermanent, you see that holding on to something is going to cause suffering.

350
00:33:32,244 --> 00:33:35,009
When you see that something is impermanent, how can it be substantial?

351
00:33:35,869 --> 00:33:36,611
How can it be me?

352
00:33:37,451 --> 00:33:40,875
Every time I point to, well, this is what I am, it's gone, it's changed, something else.

353
00:33:41,356 --> 00:33:41,457
Yeah.

354
00:33:44,103 --> 00:33:48,709
And we say of people who are stuck in views, for instance, we call them opinionated.

355
00:33:51,573 --> 00:33:58,281
But a definition of a self is that it's whole, entire, doesn't move, knows where it is, stuck.

356
00:33:58,603 --> 00:33:59,084
You know what I mean?

357
00:33:59,104 --> 00:33:59,984
It's like solid.

358
00:34:01,666 --> 00:34:11,780
But when you look at your phenomenal being, like the sensations you get from your body, your feelings in your heart, the thoughts in your mind,

359
00:34:13,211 --> 00:34:14,873
They're constantly in this process of change.

360
00:34:15,434 --> 00:34:17,996
You can't point to something, you can't say, well, I am happy.

361
00:34:18,057 --> 00:34:18,297
See?

362
00:34:19,018 --> 00:34:20,260
One minute you say, I am happy.

363
00:34:21,141 --> 00:34:22,302
Next minute, I'm depressed.

364
00:34:24,043 --> 00:34:24,704
Where's his I?

365
00:34:24,925 --> 00:34:25,907
Where's his I to be found?

366
00:34:29,490 --> 00:34:33,454
If you say, well, I was, I was happy, well, that's of course, that's dead.

367
00:34:35,077 --> 00:34:40,282
If you try and extend your I beyond the present moment, you're losing existence.

368
00:34:40,668 --> 00:34:41,869
I will be happy.

369
00:34:41,889 --> 00:34:43,132
That's a waste of time, that is.

370
00:34:43,592 --> 00:34:44,373
I want to be happy now.

371
00:34:46,836 --> 00:35:03,621
So being aware of impermanence is a sort of gateway into the other two.

372
00:35:09,253 --> 00:35:18,795
He reinforces this in the Mangala Sutta, the Sutta, the discourse on the highest blessings, not to associate with fools, but to associate with the wise, to honour those worthy of honour.

373
00:35:20,659 --> 00:35:26,992
And then relationship with the teacher, this Kalyanamita, the good friend,

374
00:35:28,389 --> 00:35:32,976
And he has a lovely passage here about how we can relate to a teacher.

375
00:35:33,217 --> 00:35:36,461
Here one has faith in the teacher and visits him or her.

376
00:35:37,282 --> 00:35:38,965
When he visits, he pays respect.

377
00:35:39,226 --> 00:35:40,869
When he pays respect, he gives ear.

378
00:35:41,650 --> 00:35:48,340
One who gives ear hears the Dharma and having heard the Dharma, memorizes it, examines the meaning of the teachings.

379
00:35:50,480 --> 00:35:58,489
When the teachings, when the meaning is examined, it develops the intellectual acceptance of these teachings.

380
00:35:58,608 --> 00:36:00,931
So now we're going back to this, how faith grows.

381
00:36:02,092 --> 00:36:11,724
When zeal, yes, when there is an acceptance of teaching, zeal springs up.

382
00:36:11,744 --> 00:36:12,465
That's true, isn't it?

383
00:36:12,625 --> 00:36:16,690
When you have faith in something, there's a sort of an energy comes to follow it through.

384
00:36:18,070 --> 00:36:25,621
As soon as you have confidence for the job, this sort of energy comes through.

385
00:36:25,641 --> 00:36:26,021
Zeal.

386
00:36:27,164 --> 00:36:30,108
And when zeal has sprung up, then the will is applied.

387
00:36:30,789 --> 00:36:33,032
And when the will is applied, there's a scrutiny.

388
00:36:33,052 --> 00:36:34,556
So this is the meditation now.

389
00:36:34,576 --> 00:36:43,690
And the striving, resolutely striving, realizes ultimate truth and sees it by penetrating it with intuitive intelligence.

390
00:36:45,289 --> 00:36:51,161
So there's a whole process that happens once you have that faith.

391
00:36:51,521 --> 00:36:59,737
And it can come either through the actual practice itself or through a relationship with a teacher.

392
00:37:00,840 --> 00:37:06,791
As I say, in my own case, going through various teachers,

393
00:37:07,480 --> 00:37:08,842
All inspiring.

394
00:37:10,103 --> 00:37:12,967
All of them sort of being able to point me in the right direction.

395
00:37:13,487 --> 00:37:19,135
And if I were to ask myself, would I have progressed without these people helping me?

396
00:37:20,516 --> 00:37:21,538
No, it's not possible.

397
00:37:22,438 --> 00:37:27,485
A teacher is actually kernel to the practice.

398
00:37:27,505 --> 00:37:32,492
Not that one becomes attached to the teacher, you know, my guru, that wouldn't be really where the Buddha's at.

399
00:37:32,893 --> 00:37:40,963
because the teacher is one who points, the one who instructs, one who clarifies for the student.

400
00:37:44,150 --> 00:37:51,141
I know that in certain forms of Buddhism you do get that guru thing, but it's definitely not there in the Buddha himself.

401
00:37:51,300 --> 00:38:08,588
If I remember rightly now, he's actually dying, and there's a monk looking at him in that sort of very loving, attached way of, my teacher, my guru, sends him off to the forest.

402
00:38:08,905 --> 00:38:16,778
And the reason is that that sort of attachment is again a barrier to investigating.

403
00:38:16,818 --> 00:38:20,144
It's a barrier actually to be able to criticize the teacher.

404
00:38:21,166 --> 00:38:24,552
You become fooled, can't you?

405
00:38:24,572 --> 00:38:28,179
I mean, you know, we've heard stories of people who've been fooled by gurus.

406
00:38:30,639 --> 00:38:51,266
So it's not that sort of thing, it's more to do with a respect, an openness, an ability to listen, to follow the practice, and to keep that sense of distance so that you can discriminate as to whether the teaching is actually doing you good.

407
00:38:52,128 --> 00:38:53,610
That's the point.

408
00:38:56,711 --> 00:39:07,568
Now, there are, of course, the old dangers to that undermined faith, and one of them we've already talked about, the distinction between faith and belief.

409
00:39:09,490 --> 00:39:24,052
There's a lovely discourse called the Kalama Sutta, and the Kalamas were a people who were obviously very interested in the spiritual path, this village, all these people had become very interested in

410
00:39:25,601 --> 00:39:34,793
And they complain that this guru would pass through and say, well, whatever those gurus say, that's a load of rubbish and this is the truth.

411
00:39:35,673 --> 00:39:40,639
And then the next guru would come along and say, no, no, no, they're a load of rubbish and they're completely confused.

412
00:39:41,581 --> 00:39:48,909
And when the Buddha comes, he says to them not to believe anything.

413
00:39:50,188 --> 00:40:18,762
I'll take it from this from the actual discourse because it's a bit more the translation is slightly better he said don't go by oral tradition so in those days things were handed down by you know by rote learning so just because it's oral tradition the lineage of teaching this has been a long lineage but it still might not be true I think it was Gandhi said truth can be in a minority of one

414
00:40:20,867 --> 00:40:45,643
not by hearsay somebody's told you or by a collection of scriptures so this must have been added later because the Buddha was illiterate which always comes as a shock to people but then so was everybody else didn't do any writing there was no writing the only people who had writing as such were the growing merchant classes even today

415
00:40:45,724 --> 00:40:49,231
In Hinduism, the Brahmins, they still learn it off-road.

416
00:40:49,371 --> 00:40:52,318
It's still very much part of their practice.

417
00:40:52,338 --> 00:40:53,780
Not by logical reasoning.

418
00:40:54,661 --> 00:41:00,072
Now, that might come as a surprise to a lot of people, but where's reason taken us?

419
00:41:00,594 --> 00:41:06,264
Our own enlightenment, the 18th century enlightenment, which put reason to the fore,

420
00:41:06,429 --> 00:41:09,572
and did away with tradition.

421
00:41:10,835 --> 00:41:12,235
It had to be reasonable.

422
00:41:12,255 --> 00:41:17,161
And, of course, out of that grew our whole scientific tradition and our technology.

423
00:41:17,181 --> 00:41:25,931
It's been a huge sort of exploration and a wondrous couple of hundred years, really, if you think about what's been invented.

424
00:41:28,034 --> 00:41:33,438
And it's produced the wonderful Declaration of Human Rights, the UN Declaration of Human Rights.

425
00:41:33,539 --> 00:41:35,762
So there's no mention of God in that.

426
00:41:35,827 --> 00:41:39,751
That's just human reason, you know, like how do we live peacefully together?

427
00:41:39,791 --> 00:41:41,014
What are our rights?

428
00:41:41,835 --> 00:41:44,719
But it also produced communism and Nazism.

429
00:41:45,880 --> 00:41:55,032
So reason is only, shall we say, reasoned on a premise.

430
00:41:55,351 --> 00:41:59,137
So you can reason anything once you take a premise.

431
00:41:59,177 --> 00:42:05,827
If your premise is human beings are not equal, off you go, you get a great, fantastic, you can write a book about that.

432
00:42:08,911 --> 00:42:22,572
Inferential reasoning, that's almost, you know, like for instance I have a headache, I've had headaches, so when you say you have a headache, I'm inferring that you must have the same sort of pain that I have in my head.

433
00:42:24,324 --> 00:42:25,465
He says, not even that either.

434
00:42:25,505 --> 00:42:26,987
He says, don't believe it, you see.

435
00:42:27,969 --> 00:42:31,353
Then he goes on reflection, just on your own reflection.

436
00:42:31,474 --> 00:42:34,056
Just because you've reasoned it, don't believe it.

437
00:42:34,757 --> 00:42:35,818
It's a bit heavy, isn't it?

438
00:42:37,001 --> 00:42:39,163
Or by acceptance of the view after pondering it.

439
00:42:39,422 --> 00:42:40,023
Do the same thing.

440
00:42:40,525 --> 00:42:43,447
Or by the seeming competence of the speaker.

441
00:42:44,369 --> 00:42:45,451
Be careful of that.

442
00:42:46,211 --> 00:42:47,313
Silver tongues and all that.

443
00:42:47,914 --> 00:42:51,277
Or because you think the ascetic is our teacher, the guru.

444
00:42:54,666 --> 00:43:03,643
But then he says it's only when you know for yourself these things are wholesome, these things are blamable, these things are to be censured by the wise.

445
00:43:04,585 --> 00:43:08,432
These things if undertaken and practiced lead to harm and suffering.

446
00:43:08,452 --> 00:43:09,835
Then you should abandon them.

447
00:43:09,855 --> 00:43:11,878
And then he talks about the positive side.

448
00:43:14,003 --> 00:43:14,463
So...

449
00:43:15,945 --> 00:43:24,400
It's a case of a combination of practice and reasoning.

450
00:43:24,983 --> 00:43:26,865
It's not just that you reasoned it.

451
00:43:27,947 --> 00:43:31,253
It's also your own personal experience.

452
00:43:31,273 --> 00:43:40,030
So, take for instance people who suffer from things like anxiety heavily or depression.

453
00:43:41,039 --> 00:43:54,458
what the teaching will say to them is you're causing you yourself are the cause of your own depression so I mean that's a turnaround most people think that

454
00:43:56,547 --> 00:44:04,478
You know, it's their partner that's depressing them, or the job, or the country, the prime minister, everybody's depressing them.

455
00:44:04,498 --> 00:44:05,440
They're totally depressed.

456
00:44:07,043 --> 00:44:13,632
And then suddenly this Buddhist teacher comes along and says, no, you're making yourself depressed.

457
00:44:13,652 --> 00:44:14,594
Nobody can make you depressed.

458
00:44:14,614 --> 00:44:16,277
Nobody can cause you psychological pain.

459
00:44:17,840 --> 00:44:21,204
So first a person might reject that, something absolute rubbish, you know.

460
00:44:21,268 --> 00:44:29,764
And then they say, well look, why don't you just sit quietly with me now and just watch how the mind is working.

461
00:44:33,431 --> 00:44:39,260
And then you do the meditation and you realize, oh yeah, it's me, I'm making myself depressed.

462
00:44:41,518 --> 00:44:49,309
So it's that sort of exploration, not just believing it, but actually making it true to yourself.

463
00:44:49,349 --> 00:44:50,831
So it's all these things, really.

464
00:44:51,172 --> 00:44:55,117
He says it's not just by information, not just by listening to a teacher.

465
00:44:56,358 --> 00:45:04,650
It's a combination of both the hearing, the understanding, personal reflection, personal practice, personal experience.

466
00:45:04,670 --> 00:45:08,235
And then one comes to realize, oh yeah, this is true, this is true for me.

467
00:45:13,429 --> 00:45:16,492
I mean, the Buddha knew when he was liberated.

468
00:45:18,815 --> 00:45:20,556
He knew when he'd experienced Nibbana.

469
00:45:20,577 --> 00:45:24,619
It's not as though he came off and wondered, no, what was that?

470
00:45:26,121 --> 00:45:28,164
He knew that was the end of suffering.

471
00:45:28,184 --> 00:45:30,865
He knew he was liberated as soon as he did it.

472
00:45:36,871 --> 00:45:42,896
So that's not to confuse faith with belief anyway, that's all.

473
00:45:45,762 --> 00:45:50,347
The other thing is, be careful not to be too critical.

474
00:45:51,789 --> 00:45:56,835
Because often it's all to do with what we expect from our practice.

475
00:45:56,856 --> 00:46:01,282
And it's a big, it can be a real undermining of doubt.

476
00:46:02,123 --> 00:46:05,106
People come to the practice with expectation.

477
00:46:06,168 --> 00:46:11,695
And when these expectations, when these hopes are not fulfilled, then the doubt begins.

478
00:46:11,956 --> 00:46:13,157
It's not doing me any good.

479
00:46:13,237 --> 00:46:15,280
I mean, I've come across that many a times.

480
00:46:17,047 --> 00:46:37,117
And you have to be careful of that because in a sense what expectation is doing is it's producing a future which has maybe completely contrary to the actual manifestation of the path within you.

481
00:46:38,278 --> 00:46:43,646
So just taking an instance where other people are criticizing.

482
00:46:44,538 --> 00:46:45,599
So here's a lovely thing.

483
00:46:45,880 --> 00:46:47,322
It's called the Bhaddali Sutta.

484
00:46:47,623 --> 00:46:50,726
And this monk is always doing daft things or wrong things.

485
00:46:51,447 --> 00:46:52,809
And he's always being criticized.

486
00:46:53,610 --> 00:46:56,896
And the Buddha said, this Bhikkhu progresses by way of faith and love.

487
00:46:57,757 --> 00:47:04,186
Let him not lose the measure of faith and love, as he may if we take action against him by repeatedly admonishing him.

488
00:47:05,469 --> 00:47:14,342
Suppose a man only had one eye, then his friends and companions, his kinsmen and relatives would guard that eye, thinking, let him not lose his one eye.

489
00:47:15,958 --> 00:47:20,684
So too, sambhiku progresses by measure of faith and love.

490
00:47:20,704 --> 00:47:31,059
So, that's in a sense of people with people, but even with ourselves, be careful not to note self-criticism.

491
00:47:33,422 --> 00:47:36,686
Like, I can't do this meditation, my head's going all over the place, I can't do it.

492
00:47:38,369 --> 00:47:40,751
Don't believe your own mind, that's ridiculous.

493
00:47:42,655 --> 00:47:46,264
I don't believe in anybody else's, but our own minds are liars.

494
00:47:47,086 --> 00:47:48,831
Dreadful things.

495
00:47:48,851 --> 00:47:49,733
Wouldn't bother with it really.

496
00:47:52,219 --> 00:47:56,731
Also what undermines the practice is unethical behaviour.

497
00:47:57,168 --> 00:48:04,579
It's very interesting that because when you start doing things which you know is wrong, you start losing self-respect.

498
00:48:05,340 --> 00:48:08,804
It's to do with the quality of shame, but it's sort of self-respect, self-esteem.

499
00:48:09,246 --> 00:48:14,614
And this, as it were, poisons everything you do because it undermines your confidence in yourself.

500
00:48:16,938 --> 00:48:25,791
It can have quite an undermining effect on your life to do things which you feel are wrong, you know, which are not quite right.

501
00:48:33,128 --> 00:48:45,965
And this business of expectation, those of you who received my newsletter and actually read it, I don't read newsletters, I'm not one to blame anybody else.

502
00:48:48,047 --> 00:48:55,456
You'll see I had a little essay in there trying to discern between expectation, aspiration and hope.

503
00:48:57,242 --> 00:49:08,759
What expectation does is it puts a completion date on things, it puts an ideal ahead of you and therefore you torture life to fit in with that ideal.

504
00:49:10,581 --> 00:49:19,715
I remember I met somebody who said they'd gone on a meditation retreat and he'd read the books and it was about achieving liberation, Nibbāna.

505
00:49:20,275 --> 00:49:23,840
So he went on a course, he'd gone on a meditation course

506
00:49:24,157 --> 00:49:29,733
So it's, you know, like if you go on a course to get a certificate for woodwork, at the end you get your certificate.

507
00:49:30,576 --> 00:49:34,686
So he joined a week's course in meditation and he'd get Nibbana.

508
00:49:39,260 --> 00:49:40,141
Years later.

509
00:49:42,146 --> 00:49:43,309
It's a bit of an awakening, you see.

510
00:49:43,509 --> 00:49:44,369
It's not quite like that.

511
00:49:45,411 --> 00:49:46,932
So that's what expectation is.

512
00:49:47,914 --> 00:49:49,295
Aspiration is something different.

513
00:49:49,416 --> 00:49:54,422
Aspiration is something that comes from the heart.

514
00:49:54,663 --> 00:49:58,809
It's not so solid.

515
00:49:59,590 --> 00:50:01,391
It's knowing where you want to go.

516
00:50:01,472 --> 00:50:03,195
It's sort of a general direction.

517
00:50:03,255 --> 00:50:06,338
The Buddha talks about inclining to Nibbāna.

518
00:50:06,358 --> 00:50:07,059
Inclining.

519
00:50:08,240 --> 00:50:11,125
If you stand still and lean forward, you have to take a step.

520
00:50:13,400 --> 00:50:23,010
And it's an aspiration, it's a sort of desire, it can be a very strong desire to aspire to become a Buddha, for instance.

521
00:50:25,233 --> 00:50:30,820
But there's no time limit on it, there's nothing put around that, it's just the heart's desire.

522
00:50:31,581 --> 00:50:36,065
And that's a great freedom and it's a great motivator.

523
00:50:37,581 --> 00:50:43,088
is often used in the sense of good wishes, you know, well I hope you're well, or I hope you do this, or I hope I get the job.

524
00:50:45,150 --> 00:50:53,119
But I like to use the word hope in its sort of, if I want a better word, theological meaning, in the way that Christians use it.

525
00:50:54,219 --> 00:51:00,686
Hope is that sort of inner knowledge that comes to you through your practice that there is an end to suffering.

526
00:51:02,454 --> 00:51:10,202
And that puts this underlying hope in your life, this underlying joy in your life that there is actually an end to suffering.

527
00:51:12,250 --> 00:51:14,659
You know, there is an end to suffering.

528
00:51:14,909 --> 00:51:19,173
And that sort of is a bedrock for our lives.

529
00:51:19,233 --> 00:51:24,039
If that becomes really strong in you, it's a bedrock.

530
00:51:24,099 --> 00:51:25,902
Because nothing, it doesn't matter what happens.

531
00:51:26,061 --> 00:51:38,958
If you end up in a Chinese prison as a political prisoner or something, see, underneath it there runs this knowledge that even this too will pass.

532
00:51:39,057 --> 00:51:42,641
That there is an actual end to suffering.

533
00:51:42,661 --> 00:51:44,224
Without that, there's, you know, like

534
00:51:45,976 --> 00:51:46,476
What is there?

535
00:51:46,536 --> 00:51:47,157
Despair.

536
00:51:47,237 --> 00:51:52,603
So, just making that sort of little distinction there.

537
00:51:53,625 --> 00:51:56,389
But here's the Buddha, you see, in a Katagiri Sutta.

538
00:51:56,429 --> 00:52:03,177
He says, I do not say that the attainment of profound knowledge comes straight away.

539
00:52:03,237 --> 00:52:11,427
Nevertheless, the attainment of profound knowledge comes by gradual training, a gradual doing, a gradual course.

540
00:52:12,097 --> 00:52:19,353
And how does the attainment of profound knowledge come by means of gradual training, gradual doing, gradual course?

541
00:52:19,373 --> 00:52:23,021
As it is monks, one who has faith draws near.

542
00:52:24,003 --> 00:52:26,588
Drawing near, they sit nearby.

543
00:52:27,632 --> 00:52:29,735
Sitting nearby, they lend an ear.

544
00:52:29,918 --> 00:52:34,724
Lending an ear, they hear the Dharma, and having heard the Dharma, they remember it.

545
00:52:35,465 --> 00:52:42,271
They test the meaning of things born in the mind, and while testing the meaning, the things are approved of.

546
00:52:43,733 --> 00:52:46,898
There being approved of, desire is born.

547
00:52:47,498 --> 00:52:51,923
Now this is the aspiration, not desire in the sensual sense.

548
00:52:51,943 --> 00:52:59,773
And when aspiration, I think I prefer that word, aspiration is born, they make an effort, and having made an effort, they weigh it up.

549
00:53:00,309 --> 00:53:12,130
Having weighed it up, they strive, and being self-resolute, they realize for themselves the highest truth itself, penetrating by the means of wisdom they see.

550
00:53:13,532 --> 00:53:15,096
It's a gradual process.

551
00:53:28,271 --> 00:53:31,675
And I'll be talking about this just a bit more tomorrow.

552
00:53:32,536 --> 00:53:39,663
But also that lack of faith in the teacher, the Dharma, the Sangha, the training.

553
00:53:40,362 --> 00:53:45,007
And he also says in being angry and displeased with one's companions in the holy life.

554
00:53:45,027 --> 00:53:47,610
I mean, that's happened.

555
00:53:47,990 --> 00:53:55,797
I know people who become very displeased with their companions and shot off somewhere, you know.

556
00:53:56,909 --> 00:54:01,934
But I want to tell you though that this business of expectation is a real killer.

557
00:54:03,295 --> 00:54:24,317
When I first started we used to do these long retreats and I met this man who became a friend and it was the way the Mahasi system teaches it, I don't teach it like that at all, but it gives you goals to go for.

558
00:54:24,483 --> 00:54:29,407
And this particular friend of mine really got involved in trying to achieve these goals.

559
00:54:30,268 --> 00:54:34,592
And I was there, looking back now, I was there when he gave up the practice.

560
00:54:38,275 --> 00:54:40,077
It was a kernel moment in his life.

561
00:54:40,097 --> 00:54:43,000
I mean, I didn't realize how kernel it was, of course.

562
00:54:43,840 --> 00:54:52,447
But he dropped, like, he was one of these people that did six-month retreats and then six months of strength, drug and rock and roll.

563
00:54:55,717 --> 00:55:00,342
And although he said, hey, I mean, boy, if somebody could meditate, this man could.

564
00:55:02,204 --> 00:55:07,047
But because he hadn't achieved it, he sort of lost the faith, he lost confidence, lost confidence in himself.

565
00:55:07,809 --> 00:55:10,690
Couldn't do it, not this lifetime, that sort of argument.

566
00:55:10,710 --> 00:55:11,552
And he dropped.

567
00:55:11,572 --> 00:55:12,672
And I lost contact.

568
00:55:13,112 --> 00:55:15,375
Ten years later, he turns up and we meet.

569
00:55:15,574 --> 00:55:20,719
And that year, he told me, this is a while back when money was, you know, money.

570
00:55:22,021 --> 00:55:25,623
He'd just spent £8,000 on crack.

571
00:55:26,059 --> 00:55:31,849
So it's quite a danger to fall into the error of expectation.

572
00:55:33,512 --> 00:55:41,125
Expect nothing.

573
00:55:41,144 --> 00:55:46,414
So I think that just about brings us to the end of our little discussion of faith.

574
00:55:50,782 --> 00:55:55,798
Not another nice story to end with.

575
00:55:55,818 --> 00:55:57,945
An admonishment.

576
00:55:57,965 --> 00:55:58,768
An exaltation.

577
00:55:58,809 --> 00:56:00,775
Don't expect anything.

578
00:56:15,300 --> 00:56:25,672
So, faith is a sort of core, basic attitude within us which we can develop through our practice, you know.

579
00:56:25,692 --> 00:56:43,771
And if you feel your confidence declining, if you feel your confidence going, you know, try to see that something is happening there which is undermining, try to see what is actually undermining your confidence, you see.

580
00:56:43,751 --> 00:56:48,998
Even not keeping resolutions can undermine your confidence.

581
00:56:49,699 --> 00:57:00,434
So often people will say, beginners come to meditation and they make this big determination of they're going to sit for two hours in the morning and two hours in the evening, you know, and it lasts till Monday.

582
00:57:01,876 --> 00:57:03,478
And then they can't do it.

583
00:57:04,099 --> 00:57:05,001
They can't do it.

584
00:57:07,175 --> 00:57:14,929
So it's really just being aware of how easily we can undermine ourselves.

585
00:57:16,512 --> 00:57:25,469
And in states of doubt, they'll always come up until we've achieved that sort of deep insight into things.

586
00:57:26,648 --> 00:57:28,269
and not to be fooled by doubt.

587
00:57:28,489 --> 00:57:38,061
Often it's an honest doubt which the Buddha would want, a state of confusion, and just to stay in that and just to feel how uncomfortable it is.

588
00:57:38,782 --> 00:57:44,588
We don't like to be in a place of not knowing, very uncomfortable, a lot of fear and anxiety in there.

589
00:57:44,608 --> 00:57:47,592
So this is a real teaching because

590
00:57:48,197 --> 00:57:49,619
You know, in some sense we don't know.

591
00:57:50,500 --> 00:57:51,621
There are lots of things we don't know.

592
00:57:51,721 --> 00:57:54,023
You don't know whether you'll be here tomorrow.

593
00:57:54,043 --> 00:57:56,626
You might be up there or down there.

594
00:57:56,646 --> 00:57:56,947
Who knows?

595
00:57:57,487 --> 00:57:58,847
You don't know, do you?

596
00:57:58,867 --> 00:57:59,409
You just don't know.

597
00:57:59,449 --> 00:58:02,512
You don't know what's going to happen.

598
00:58:02,532 --> 00:58:09,159
And it's living in that don't know place which is very instructive and just to stay there.

599
00:58:09,559 --> 00:58:17,867
Often we can't make a decision until more information comes in, until we have more experience, until there's a clarification.

600
00:58:18,521 --> 00:58:22,907
Not to push the process because we don't like staying in that position of not knowing.

601
00:58:28,411 --> 00:58:43,407
And when it comes to the growth of faith, like taking refuges tomorrow, to see it as a, for some of you who haven't done it, to see it just as a trial.

602
00:58:44,548 --> 00:58:47,652
How does it feel when I commit myself to a path

603
00:58:48,137 --> 00:58:49,523
For one month, one year.

604
00:58:49,583 --> 00:58:51,813
One year is better, right?

605
00:58:51,833 --> 00:58:53,278
One month goes too quick.

606
00:58:53,298 --> 00:58:54,483
How does it feel?

607
00:58:54,684 --> 00:58:56,713
At the end of that year, what's gone?

608
00:58:57,840 --> 00:58:59,543
Has some indecision gone?

609
00:58:59,583 --> 00:59:02,266
Has some clarity come?

610
00:59:02,286 --> 00:59:06,690
And remember, it's in the commitment that one can really begin to investigate.

611
00:59:06,831 --> 00:59:11,956
Because remember, so long as the commitment isn't there, there's always that pulling off, there's always that shying away.

612
00:59:14,579 --> 00:59:20,106
So, hopefully, these words of mine have been of some assistance.

613
00:59:21,507 --> 00:59:27,594
May you be liberated in this very lifetime, sooner rather than later.

